50|$|The <b>chestnut-headed</b> <b>sparrow-lark</b> (Eremopterix signatus) or {{chestnut-headed finch-lark}} is {{a species of}} {{passerine}} bird in the family Alaudidae. It is found in eastern and north-eastern Africa. Its natural habitats are subtropical or tropical dry shrubland, subtropical or tropical dry lowland grassland, and hot deserts.|$|E
50|$|The male <b>chestnut-headed</b> <b>sparrow-lark</b> has a black {{collar and}} bib, white cheeks {{and a white}} {{circular}} area on the nape of the crown, surrounded by a chestnut border. This distinguishes it from Fischer's sparrow-lark which lacks the white spot. The female has duller plumage.|$|E
50|$|This {{inconspicuous}} dull-coloured bird somewhat {{resembles a}} finch. It {{can be distinguished}} from the similar <b>chestnut-headed</b> <b>sparrow-lark</b> {{by the absence of}} a white patch on the crown of its head. It is found on short grass plains where it congregates in large flocks except during the breeding season.|$|E

